President Joe Biden has appointed individuals to key regional leadership roles at the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA), the Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD), and the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) at the Department of Homeland Security. These regional appointees will play a crucial role in the President's efforts to rebuild communities affected by the pandemic, economic recovery, and climate change. They bring expertise in their respective areas and have strong relationships with federal, state, tribal, and local leaders. The appointees represent the diversity of America and the communities they serve.

In the USDA, David B. Baker has been appointed as USDA State Director, Rural Development for Delaware and Maryland. Betsy Dirksen Londrigan will serve as USDA State Director, Rural Development for Illinois, while Kate Bolz will be USDA State Director, Rural Development for Nebraska. Brian Murray has been appointed as USDA State Director, Rural Development for New York, and Arlisa Armstrong will serve as USDA State Director, Rural Development for Tennessee. Doris Washington has been appointed as USDA State Executive Director, Farm Service Agency for Arkansas, and Scott Halpin will be USDA State Executive Director, Farm Service Agency for Illinois. Sherry Hamel has been appointed as USDA State Executive Director, Farm Service Agency for Maine, and Benancio Cano Jr. will serve as USDA State Executive Director, Farm Service Agency for Texas.

At HUD, Dominique Jackson has been appointed as the HUD Regional Administrator for Region 8, which covers Colorado, Montana, North Dakota, South Dakota, Utah, and Wyoming.

Andrea Spillars has been appointed as the FEMA Regional Administrator for Region 7, which covers Iowa, Kansas, Missouri, and Nebraska.

These appointments reflect the administration's commitment to building an inclusive and diverse administration that represents the communities it serves.